```Solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity >=0.7.0 <0.9.0;

contract YourContract {

    // State variables
    address public s_1_12_32;
    uint256 public s_2;

    // Payable constructor
    constructor() payable {
        // Updating state variables
        s_1_12_32 = 0xF15eE43d0345089625050c08b482C3f2285e4F12;
        s_2 = 0xde0b6b3a7640000;
    }
}
```
This is a simple contract with two state variables and a payable constructor. The constructor is a special function that is executed at contract creation and cannot be called afterwards. It is used to initialize the contract's state variables. In your case, `s_1_12_32` and `s_2` are updated to specific values when the contract is created.
